data.content:
Your code **does not use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.Interrupt`, or `ThreadAbortException`. The APIs it does use — `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — work identically in .NET 8 and require **no migration**.

That said, you could modernize it by replacing raw threads with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.WhenAll`:

```csharp
public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
{
    await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, async (item, ct) =>
    {
        await Task.Delay(100, ct);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    });
}
```

This gives you built-in cancellation support via `CancellationToken` — the modern replacement for `Thread.Abort` — should you need it in the future.
